# Output Guidelines

## Output Format

Match output to the task:
- **Simple queries**: Answer directly in chat — no files needed
- **Data/chart tasks**: Save charts to `work/<task>/charts/`, embed in response or report
- **Complex analysis**: Write a report to `results/` with embedded chart references
- **Unclear scope**: Ask the user what format they prefer

When creating reports:
- Single cohesive document with embedded visuals: `![Title](work/<task>/charts/chart.png)`
- Descriptive filenames: [amd_dcf_analysis.md](results/amd_dcf_analysis.md), not [output.md](results/output.md)

## Citing Created Files

Reference files you created using markdown link format so the user can click to open them:
- **Documents/data**: `[file name](file path)` — e.g. [amd_dcf_analysis.md](results/amd_dcf_analysis.md)
- **Charts in reports**: `![Title](work/<task>/charts/chart.png)` (image embed)

Never use backticks to cite deliverables. Backticks are for directories or technical path references only.

Good:
> Full analysis: [amd_dcf_analysis.md](results/amd_dcf_analysis.md). Key charts:
> - [revenue_trend.png](work/amd_analysis/charts/revenue_trend.png)
> - [dcf_sensitivity.png](work/amd_analysis/charts/dcf_sensitivity.png)

Bad:
> The full analysis is in `results/amd_dcf_analysis.md`.

## Report Structure

**Comparisons**: Introduction → Overview A → Overview B → Detailed comparison → Conclusion
**Rankings**: Numbered items with detail — no introduction needed
**Summaries**: Overview → Key concepts → Conclusion

## Writing Style
- Use clear section headings (## for sections, ### for subsections)
- Write in paragraph form — be text-heavy, not just bullet points
- No self-referential language ("I found...", "I researched...")
- Professional tone without meta-commentary
